1. Can we Active the module on AVMS server after adding?

2. I accidently type a wrong FSN:
$ ./avms_interface -a -f T6950642191512   //T6950642191510
The script finds the available AT port and add the module to AVMS server. But on AVMS server, the module FSN is wrong, IMEI is correct. In this case, can we do a checking, give a warning message, and add the correct FSN and/or IMEI to the AVMS server?

1. No. We cannot activate on AVMS after adding; we also never need to do this. All we need to do is add module to AVMS to use FOTA.

Following up; any parameters that you manually enter (override) are assumed to be correct. Ie. if you enter '--fsn 12312123123231' the tool will not verify that this matches the FSN of the module you want to add. There is no need to do a 'double check'. 
If we are worried about entering something incorrectly, the safe method is just to do './avms_interface -a -p /dev/ttyUSB1' and it will correctly get all parameters from /dev/ttyUSB1

Hi Mary, can you please re-visit this review?
If you manually enter an FSN we should assume that it is entered correctly; if we double-check the FSN there is no reason to even allow manually entering the FSN in the first place.
In most cases the tool should just be used with './avms_interface -a -p /dev/ttyUSBX', to add a particular module (specified by the port entered) to AVMS

>

> If you manually enter an FSN we should assume that it is entered correctly; if we double-check the FSN there is no reason to even allow manually entering the FSN in the first place.
> In most cases the tool should just be used with './avms_interface -a -p /dev/ttyUSBX', to add a particular module (specified by the port entered) to AVMS

Hi, Ben,
Although a user is recommended to config with default or a port option as the 1st choice, he should be allowed to config FSN, IMEI and name regardless the port is connected:
- If valid port is connected, we should allow FSN and IMEI to be configured, can give a warning msg such as "port xxx is connected, ignore user config -f -i option"
- If port is not connected or is not valid or has error, FSN and IMEI are as the user configured.

We should consider some error handling for scenarios such as:
1. type error
2. when multiple ports are opened, a user might configure wrong FSN/IMEI on an un-intentional port
The code should be smart to correct this kind of error.

> Although a user is recommended to config with default or a port option as the 1st choice, he should be allowed to config FSN, IMEI and name regardless the port is connected:
> - If valid port is connected, we should allow FSN and IMEI to be configured, can give a warning msg such as "port xxx is connected, ignore user config -f -i option"
> - If port is not connected or is not valid or has error, FSN and IMEI are as the user configured.

> We should consider some error handling for scenarios such as:
> 1. type error
> 2. when multiple ports are opened, a user might configure wrong FSN/IMEI on an un-intentional port
> The code should be smart to correct this kind of error.

I will implement the following:
> - If valid port is connected, we should allow FSN and IMEI to be configured, can give a warning msg such as "port xxx is connected, ignore user config -f -i option"
> - If port is not connected or is not valid or has error, FSN and IMEI are as the user configured.
> - Input error (ie. user enters an invalid FSN)

I am hesitant to implement 'when multiple ports are opened, a user might configure wrong FSN/IMEI on an un-intentional port. The code should be smart to correct this kind of error.'

We should assume some kind of user proficiency and that they understand how to use the tool. The user should know which port corresponds to which FSN/IMEI. Otherwise, if the FSN doesn't match the Port specified, the tool would need to check ALL other existing ports just to find the right match. I feel that this is unncessary.

typo... if user connect CLI port to module, then the at command will be "at at+kgsn=3" instead of "at+kgsn=3"

If we want this tool to test connecting to the server after adding it, it must be done through the AT port. Otherwise, if this tool can be run through CLI port would need to skip testing connecting to server.

Removing or gettting module info will not be affected by this since just need the Serial Number in those cases..
